It started with a template engine.
Not because the world needed another one. Because I needed one that worked the way I think. Something that wouldn't surprise me six months later in production.
That project became Mutor.js.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

The template engine.
Most template engines either interpret your templates at runtime or do something loosely compiled that still feels like interpretation. Mutor does neither. It walks your template block by block, building and validating AST nodes as it goes. Once the full template checks out, the AST is serialized into a single JavaScript function. You call that function with a context object and it runs straight through, concatenating output. No parsing at render time. No re-validation. Just a function executing.
The syntax lives inside {{}}delimiters. Everything outside a tag is copied to output as-is. Everything inside is evaluated against whatever context object you pass in.
<h1>{{ title }}</h1>
<p>Welcome, {{ user.name }}.</p>Conditionals and loops are what you'd expect, but they compile down rather than interpret:
{{ if user.admin }}
<strong>{{ user.name }}</strong>
{{ else if user.active }}
<span>{{ user.name }}</span>
{{ else }}
<em>Inactive user</em>
{{ endif }}{{ for post of posts }}
<article>
<h2>{{ post.title }}</h2>
<p>{{ post.excerpt }}</p>
</article>
{{ endfor }}You can iterate over objects too, binding both key and value:
{{ for key, value in meta }}
<meta name="{{ key }}" content="{{ value }}">
{{ endfor }}And break and continue both work inside loops, because they compile to the JavaScript equivalents.
The expression language covers what templates actually need. Dot notation, bracket notation, optional chaining, arithmetic, comparisons, logical operators, nullish coalescing, ternaries. What it does not support is object literals, array literals, function expressions, or arbitrary JavaScript execution. Those constraints are the point. If the logic belongs in the template, it probably belongs in your application code instead.
Components and layouts.
The part that turned Mutor from a useful library into something I actually wanted to build with was the composition model.
Components are named template strings you register once and include anywhere:
mutor.registerComponent("card", `
<article>
<h2>{{ title }}</h2>
<p>{{ body }}</p>
</article>
`);Including a component inside another template is one line:
{{ ::include("card") }}By default the component inherits the full parent context. If you want to render it against a specific value from the context, pass it as a second argument:
{{ ::include("profile-card", user) }}Components can include other components. The context chain carries through at every level unless you override it. You can also inspect what a component is actually receiving at any point:
<pre>{{ JSON::stringify(::$$context, 2) }}</pre>That ::$$context shorthand exposes the full current context object. I used it constantly while building the docs site.
Layouts build on top of components. A layout declares its name at the top of the file and marks where child content gets injected:
{{# layout "root" }}
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<title>{{ title }}</title>
</head>
<body>
<nav>
{{ for item of nav }}
<a href="{{ item.href }}">{{ item.label }}</a>
{{ endfor }}
</nav>
<main>
{{ ::slot }}
</main>
</body>
</html>Any template that wants to render inside that layout just declares it at the top:
{{# use "root" }}
<h1>{{ title }}</h1>
<p>{{ description }}</p>The layout and the child template share the same context. `{{ title }}` resolves correctly in both. No prop drilling. No configuration. Two lines and it works.
Layouts can extend other layouts too. You can stack them as deep as you need and Mutor resolves the full chain, rejecting circular dependencies at registration time, not at runtime.
When you're working with files on disk, you load your layouts once at startup:
await mutor.addLayoutsInDir("./views/layouts");After that, any file template that opens with `{{# use "name" }}` gets wrapped automatically when you call `renderFile`.
The output Mutor generates is language-agnostic. HTML is just one thing it can produce. The same engine, the same syntax, works for Markdown, emails, SQL, config files, source code. Most template engines tie themselves to HTML so deeply that using them for anything else feels wrong. Mutor doesn't know or care what you're generating. It fills the template with the data you give it and hands back a string.
Then I needed a website.
The Mutor.js documentation site needed to exist. I had a template engine. I could reach for a framework for the rest. But the more I thought about it the less I wanted to. I wanted a server that returned HTML. File-based routing. Layouts. Markdown. Something that ran anywhere Node ran.
So I built Lynnix.
Lynnix is routing and SSR middleware for Node.js built around Mutor.js and designed for htmx. It works with Node's built-in HTTP module natively, with no dependencies required to get started:
import { createLynnixApp } from "lynnix";
import sendStatic from "send-static";
import * as http from "node:http";async function main() {
const serve = sendStatic("public", { index: false });
const handle = await createLynnixApp("app");
const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
serve(req, res, () => handle(req, res));
});
server.listen(3000, () => {
console.log("Server running on http://localhost:3000");
});
}
main();
If you're already on Express, it mounts as middleware:
import { createLynnixApp } from "lynnix";
import express from "express";async function main() {
const app = express();
const handler = await createLynnixApp("app");
app.use(express.static("public"));
app.use(handler);
app.listen(3000);
}
main();
createLynnixApp returns a standard (req, res) => voidhandler. It slots in anywhere that accepts one.
The filesystem is the router. A folder called dashboardmaps to /dashboard. Wrap a folder name in brackets and it becomes a dynamic segment. Double brackets and it becomes a catch-all:
app/
├── page.html → /
├── about/
│ └── page.html → /about
├── posts/
│ ├── page.html → /posts
│ └── [slug]/
│ ├── loader.js
│ └── page.html → /posts/:slug
└── [[catchall]]/
└── page.html → matches anything elseEach route directory has a set of reserved filenames. page.htmlis the full page. loader.jsexports your HTTP method handlers. middleware.jsruns before the loader. not-found.htmland error.htmlare your error boundaries.
Loaders export named functions matching HTTP methods:

// app/posts/[slug]/loader.jsexport function GET(req) {
const post = db.posts.find(req.params.slug);
if (!post) {
throw new NotFoundError();
}
return { post };
}
export function DELETE(req, res) {
db.posts.delete(req.params.slug);
res.status(200).end();
}
Whatever the loader returns becomes `data` in the template:
<!-- app/posts/[slug]/page.html -->
{{# use "root" }}
<article>
<h1>{{ data.post.title }}</h1>
<p>{{ data.post.publishedAt }}</p>
{{ HTML::safe(data.post.body) }}
</article>Middleware exports a single default function and runs top-down from the root to the matched route. No next. Returning continues the chain:
// app/dashboard/middleware.jsexport default function(req, res) {
if (!req.cookies.auth) {
res.redirect("/sign-in");
return;
}
req.user = db.users.find(req.cookies.auth);
}
— -
The htmx piece.
Every htmx project ends up with this in every route:
if (req.headers["hx-request"]) {
return renderFragment();
}return renderPage();
It works. It's just the same check everywhere, forever.
Lynnix reads the HX-Request header and decides what to render automatically. Full navigation gets page.html. htmx request gets fragment.html. The loader doesn't change. The data doesn't change. You write both files and Lynnix figures out which one to send:
app/posts/
├── page.html ← served on full navigation
├── fragment.html ← served on htmx request
└── loader.js ← same loader, feeds bothThe response object speaks htmx natively too. All the response headers htmx understands are methods you can call directly. On non-htmx requests they're no-ops, so you call them freely without wrapping in conditionals:
export function POST(req, res) {
db.posts.create(req.body);
res.htmxTrigger("posts:updated");
res.htmxPush("/posts");
res.status(200).end();
}Where I ended up.
I didn't plan any of this. I built a template engine because I needed one. The documentation site forced a framework into existence. Each tool came from needing the next thing.
Mutor handles templates, compiling them once into functions that run without re-parsing. Lynnix handles routing, middleware chains, data loading, and rendering, and knows how to respond to htmx without being told every time. They fit together because Lynnix was built with Mutor from the start.
I still reach for React when the project calls for it. This isn't a position paper.
But every server-rendered application I start now begins here. Not because I think it's objectively correct. Because after building these tools and then using them on real projects, I stopped spending energy on the framework and started spending it on the product.
The best thing a tool can do is disappear. These ones finally did.
